metadata.name: Learning to Fly #40
metadata.description:
This artwork renders a paper canvas-like texture and creates curves mimicking strokes of an ink pen.

It's coded entirely in p5.js and is best viewed on a screen bigger than a mobile phone, while listening to this track called ‘Learning to Fly' by Pink Floyd: 
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nVhNCTH8pDs

Artwork loads at 1000px by 1000px resolution by default. Press ‘2’,’4’ or ‘8’ to load as 2000px by 2000px, 4000px by 4000px or 8000px by 8000px respectively.

Press 's' at any time to download the rendered resolution.

metadata.name: Acequia #80
metadata.description:
Acequia (“ah-seh-kee-uh”) - a Spanish adaptation of the Arabic word as-sāqiya, meaning “water carrier”. 

In our second collaboration, Rich and Rick are back with our blend of generative code, intricate design, attention to detail, and a splash of charm. 

 Acequias are traditional irrigation canals used to distribute rainwater and snowmelt along a complex network of narrow channels. They are found in Spain, the American Southwest, and northern Mexico, where they are essential for sustaining fields, orchards, and gardens in semi-arid regions.   
Our aim in this series is to capture the essence of these waterways in bold geometric designs. Each piece is inspired by a mountain village or town in Andalusia (southern Spain). 

The location determines the cube designs and construction rules that are used to build the final output. These are combined with striking day/night palettes, outline styles, scales, climates, and a few surprises of course!


Controls (in live view): 

- Press [p] to pause water animation 
- Press [e] to complete water animation 
- Press [r] to reset water animation 
- Press [s] to save the current image 
- Press [h] for a high-res output suitable for printing 
- Press [b] to toggle the border

metadata.name: Different Intersections - Iteration 4 #214
metadata.description:
This is the culmination of a series of iterations

____ - Iteration 1
____ - Iteration 2
____ - Iteration 3

The iterations were released under the pseudonym Extracurricular Activities.

The algorithmic theme of the iterations was extensive usage of boolean operations (intersection and difference) on polygons to derive interesting composite shapes.

In live mode, add &size=<YOUR_PIXEL_SIZE> to change the pixel size of the image for export (Right click to save). For example, &size=4000 will set the width of the image to be 4000 pixels.

metadata.name: Floating Medusas #16
metadata.description:
Floating Medusas is a generative piece. A group of little creatures creating an organic visual. 

The size, position and frequency of creatures are generated for each token, along with the color theme.  Each creature is masking by a geometric pattern. Creatures have straight or smooth edges.
The shapes’s sizes of the patterns are visible as features, like the edge’s type and the number of creatures.  

Handmade by code with javascript, made with fragment.tools 
Quentin Hocdé, Brussels (Belgium), 2022

metadata.name: Bloom in the rain #84
metadata.description:
In the oriental ink and wash paintings, the plain nature and the poetic charm are admired. The seemingly lonely scenery can often reflect the noble sentiment of the literati. In this work, I create a poetic, raining scenery by p5.js. I also reproduce the ink rhythm and texture strokes pattern left by the brush on the rice paper. This is my preliminary exploration of generative art with the form and style of oriental aesthetics.

Created purely with p5.js.
For best result, open in live view 
and press [s] to save a png

Features:
1)	pallete: whiteBackground | darkBackground | color ink
2)	rock position: left | center | right 
3)	number of tree: one | two | three
4)	rain: none | drizzle | shower | heavy | extremely heavy
5)	background type: mountain | ocean 
6)	composition: horizontal_long | horizontal | square
7)	invert color: true | false
8)	moon type: full | slender

This is an original work created by Pingyeh Li, Sep 2022.
License: CC BY-NC-SA 4.0 https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0/ - @Pingyeh Li
